{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17160"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17160"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0,0.04,0.92,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9850"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62513"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8423"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sarcoplasmic reticulum represents a specialised organelle unique to muscle tissue. This membrane network extends throughout muscle fibres and is essential for their proper function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main physiological role of the sarcoplasmic reticulum in muscle cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transport of sodium and potassium ions","Storage of glycogen for energy","Synthesis of contractile proteins","Storage and release of calcium ions","Production of adenosine triphosphate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sarcoplasmic reticulum\u0027s principal role involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Estorage and release of calcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E. During muscle activation, depolarisation spreads through T-tubules and activates voltage-sensitive proteins. These proteins interact with ryanodine receptors to release stored calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. The released calcium then interacts with troponin C to enable muscle contraction. During relaxation, specialised calcium ATPase proteins actively transport calcium back into the sarcoplasmic reticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative functions suggested in the incorrect options are handled by other cellular components:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of sodium and potassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E occurs via membrane-bound ion channels and pumps\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of glycogen for energy\u003C/strong\u003E takes place within the muscle cell cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis of contractile proteins\u003C/strong\u003E occurs on free ribosomes in the cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of adenosine triphosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by mitochondria through cellular respiration\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis calcium handling system enables precise control over muscle contraction and relaxation cycles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The sarcoplasmic reticulum functions as the main calcium ion reservoir in muscle cells.","Muscle contraction begins when T-tubule depolarisation triggers calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","Calcium reuptake into the sarcoplasmic reticulum occurs via ATP-dependent calcium pumps during muscle relaxation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62513"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62513"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:15:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:17:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9850"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emo